metadata.name: Kaleidoscopic Nexus #15
metadata.description:
Kaleidoscopic Nexus explores the dynamic interplay of vibrant colors and intricate patterns, creating a mosaic-like effect reminiscent of a kaleidoscope. 

This piece evokes a sense of intricate complexity and vibrant energy. I aimed to create an overlapping array of patterns and vivid colors that form a mosaic-like effect, reminiscent of a kaleidoscope. By blending elements of digital art with a psychedelic aesthetic, I wanted to convey a dynamic and almost hypnotic quality. The dense arrangement of geometric shapes and diverse color palette reflects my meticulous approach to crafting this piece, inviting viewers to explore its depth and discover new patterns or shapes within the chaos. For me, it symbolizes the intricate nature of systems, networks, and the interconnectedness of various elements in a digital or abstract realm.

To interact with and explore the intricate details of "Kaleidoscopic Nexus" the following keyboard controls are available, enhancing your view of the fine details and patterns and allowing you to explore different sections of this artwork. The panning speed adjusts according to the zoom level, ensuring smooth navigation.

. Zoom In (+ or = key)
. Zoom Out (- key)
. Pan Up (Arrow Up key)
. Pan Down (Arrow Down key)
. Pan Left (Arrow Left key)
. Pan Right (Arrow Right key)
. Save PNG Image (s or S key)

metadata.name: f-emerald #222
metadata.description:
f-emerald generates unique ephemeral crystal-like structures that morph in space. each generation has a different shape, animation and colour palette. 

the crystals flicker with colours in the dark most of the time. there is, however, a 20% chance of obtaining a crystal on a bright background with a light colour palette and one out of ten structures is created in black and white.

metadata.name: Giants of the Meadow #135
metadata.description:
For my first drop on the new fxhash v1.0 I wanted to make something different. So I challenged myself to write a raymarcher like the ones I use in my shaders but in p5.js and make a fully procedural scene with it. It's a bit tricky to work with vectors once you are used to GLSL, but I managed to write a decent algorithm that scans a grid and slowly draws the image. It draws it with circles and triangles for the grass. The first thing I used for testing was a SDF of a plane with some tall bars on it. Then I was trying different distortions on the shapes and in one moment the results gave me the idea of a scene with mushrooms and grass on an undulated terrain. Later I added a small river and a cloudy sky. I think I was inadvertently inspired by some children's books I had when I was a kid. 

Best viewed full screen.

Features:

Mood: happy - normal - melancholic - strange - sleepy
Mushrooms: 2 - 4 (sometimes one of the mushrooms can only be seen on full screen)
Mushroom height: short - medium - tall
Mushroom fatness: S - M - L - XL
Mushroom shape: 1 - 2 - 3- 4 - 5
Mushroom tilt
Flowers color: white - yellow - pink - cyan - multicolor
River: yes - no
Camera orientation: north - south

metadata.name: Taiga #254
metadata.description:
Generate Tall pines, spruces in atmospheric environment. I need to draw anything I feel around, any story, any relations and any environment. colors are beautiful but can not describe many moments and many atmospheres. this gray scale feeling is about my world. Feeling full of loneliness and sadness, but I know it's generated in my mind. it's not real!

All is generative! Features and variations exist in tree types, atmosphere background-foregrounds, flyings.

=========== Controls ===========
🔸 Press F key to change view.
🔸 Press S key to save high resolution image.

metadata.name: CHIP #190
metadata.description:
A CHIP is being constructed by using two brushes that are painting on the board through deterministic noise, and then turned squared and pixelated and blended into each other, with colours selected from 21 different colour schemes. How many iterations, and the speed and size of the added parts determines the final composition. 

You can stop the iterations by pressing S, and download the current composition by hitting D, and restart/reload the iterations by pressing R.

Notes
The thumbnail generation takes a while and the render/iterations in non-GPU browser can be quite slow. Chrome/Firefox recommended.

metadata.name: Verdant Brut #11
metadata.description:
Verdant translates to “lush, green” and Brut means “dry, raw, or unrefined.”

This series is less about impressions of nature, or vegetal growth… but rather the vibrant, lush world that abstract art can provide and while certain iterations may serve Brutalist aesthetics, it tries to focus on the unrefined/raw aspect of the definition with more fluid shapes that feel irregular and organic in a playful, almost adolescent way.

Palettes inspired by MOMO, Melissa Wiederrecht, Erik Swahn, Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, Paul Klee, Mareva Millarc, Ernst Mether-Borgström, Douglas Herbert Courtenay Auburn, Jim Harris, Alayne Spafford, Man Ray, Lajos Kassak and William Lachance. While the palettes may not always reflect their trademark colors (if they even have any) they are an homage to individual pieces by the respective artists that have influenced this series in their own way.

4878 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries.

For more info on the chosen palettes and other inspirations, see article linked from the main project page: Regarding Verdant Brut

In live mode:
‘S’ : save as png (2376 × 3360)
’V’ : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
‘g=n’ : no grain
‘g=p’ : paper grain
‘h=t’ : high resolution mode, 5940 × 8400 (Chrome only)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append “&g=p&h=t” to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save the png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: SCRIBBLERS #3
metadata.description:
Generative animated drawing inspired by mindless doodling and low-res CAD graphics. Custom physics engine made with vanilla javascript. Colors quantized with GLSL. By @galoandstuff.
